{
    "title": "Tonga profile - Timeline",
    "link": "https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-pacific-16199671",
    "content": [
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "A chronology of key events:",
                    "style": "bold"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "image",
            "content": "https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/ace/standard/224/mcs/media/images/57356000/jpg/_57356729_danceiii.jpg"
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                "Dancers perform the Kailao wearing traditional ta'ovalas - waist mats"
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1616",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Dutch explorers are the first Europeans to visit Tonga."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1773-77",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- British explorer Captain James Cook visits Tonga three times."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1820s",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Wesleyan Methodist missionaries arrive from England."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1830s",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Wesleyan missionaries convert paramount chief Taufa'ahau Tupou who in turn converts fellow islanders."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "British protectorate",
                    "style": "bold"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1875",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Taufa'ahau Tupou assumes the name of George Tupou I and establishes Tongan monarchy."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1900",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Tonga becomes a British protected state but is not formally colonised."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1918-65",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Reign of Queen Salote Tupou III."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1953",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Queen Saltote visits Britain for the coronation of Elizabeth II as Queen."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "image",
            "content": "https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/ace/standard/304/mcs/media/images/57345000/jpg/_57345325_queen.jpg"
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                "Queen Saltote visited Buckingham Palace in 1953"
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1958",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Tonga acquires greater autonomy from Britain."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1965",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Taufa'ahau Tupou becomes king following his mother's death."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "Independence",
                    "style": "bold"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1970",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Tonga ceases to be a British protectorate and becomes fully independent within the British Commonwealth."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1988",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Tonga signs agreement allowing US nuclear warships to pass through its waters."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1992",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Pro-Democracy Movement founded. Tongan schoolchildren perform the Kailao dance"
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1994",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Tonga's first political party, the Tonga Democratic Party - subsequently renamed the People's Party - founded by Pro-Democracy Movement."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1999",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Pro-democracy movement organises convention to discuss new, more democratic constitution."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2000",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "January - King's youngest son, Prince 'Ulukalala Lavaka Ata, appointed prime minister."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "Scandal",
                    "style": "bold"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2001",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "October - Financial scandal rocks the islands after $26 million of state money is lost in investments made by the king's official court jester, a US businessman."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2003",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "October - Changes to the constitution are made, giving greater powers to the king and increasing state control of the media."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2004",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "February - Former court jester agrees to pay $1m to settle legal dispute with Tonga."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2004",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "May - National airline, Royal Tongan Airlines, closes after running out of cash for repairs."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "image",
            "content": "https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/ace/standard/304/mcs/media/images/57544000/jpg/_57544887_riot.jpg"
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                "Pro-democracy rioting in 2006 destroyed much of the capital's business district"
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2005",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "March - Elected MPs enter the cabinet for the first time. Cabinet members had previously been picked by the royal family."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "Protest",
                    "style": "bold"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2005",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "July-August - Prolonged strike by public sector workers is accompanied by violence in the capital."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2005",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "September - Thousands of people march through the capital, demanding democratic reform."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2005",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "December - World Trade Organisation (WTO) agrees to admit Tonga as its 150th member. Negotiations had been ongoing for a decade."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2006",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "March - Feleti Sevele becomes PM - the first elected commoner to do so - following the resignation of Prince 'Ulukalala Lavaka Ata."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "image",
            "content": "https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/ace/standard/304/mcs/media/images/57351000/jpg/_57351621_volcano.jpg"
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                "Around 36 volcanos are clustered in the area off the island of Tongatapau"
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2006",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "July - Two Tongan royals - Prince Tu'ipelehake and his wife Princess Kaimana - are killed in a car crash in the US."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2006",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "September - King Taufa'ahau Tupou IV dies after a long illness. He is succeeded by his eldest son Crown Prince Tupouto'a."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "Riots",
                    "style": "bold"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2006",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "November - Rioting erupts in the capital Nuku'alofa, apparently in protest at the lack of democratic reforms. Eight people are killed and much of the business district is destroyed. State of emergency is declared."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2007",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "February - State of emergency is extended; reconstruction of business district is being planned with the help of foreign aid."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "image",
            "content": "https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/ace/standard/304/mcs/media/images/57546000/jpg/_57546549_crown.jpg"
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                "2008: King Tupou V is officially crowned"
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2007",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "July - Tonga becomes the 151st member of the World Trade Organization (WTO), 12 years after applying to join."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2008",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "April - In last elections held under the old constitution, pro-democracy candidates win all nine of the elected seats in the nation's parliament."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2008",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "July - King Tupou V says he will relinquish the near-absolute power held by the monarchy, fulfilling a longstanding pledge to introduce democratic reforms."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2008",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "August - King Tupou V is officially crowned in a lavish ceremony."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2009",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "August - The Princess Ashika ferry sinks off Tonga, leaving 74 dead."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "image",
            "content": "https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/ace/standard/304/mcs/media/images/57348000/jpg/_57348327_survivors.jpg"
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                "Survivors are rescued from a ferry disaster that kills 74 in 2009"
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2009",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "September - At least nine Tongans die in a tsunami after an earthquake centred between the north Tongan island of Niuatoputapu and Samoa."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "Reform moves",
                    "style": "bold"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2009",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "November - A committee on constitutional reform recommends introducing a popularly elected parliament and reducing the monarchy to a largely ceremonial role."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2010",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "November - First vote for a popularly elected parliament."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2012",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "March - King Tupou V dies. He is succeeded by his younger brother, the former prime minister and serving High Commissioner to Australia, Prince 'Ulukalala Lavaka Ata. He takes the title King George Tupou VI."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2015",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "January - Longstanding democracy activist 'Akalisi Pohiva becomes Tonga's first non-noble prime minister after elections in November."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2017",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "August - King Tupou dissolves parliament and dismisses the prime minister, accusing the government of having tried to remove some of his powers."
            ]
        }
    ]
}